I’m not sure what to say except that it’s good.
No noticeable flaws.
Above average writing.
Good word choice as various points, enough so that I noticed it hence me mentioning it.
Any way to make it better is beyond my expertise. All my writing experience is in essays and college work, so while I’m really proficient in grammar but have almost zero experience with story writing.

As for whether you should have added chapter 4 onto the end of chapter 3, I cannot really say. You could argue that yes it should be added onto the end because of how easily they would flow together. At the same time you could argue the contrary because Vee falling asleep at the end of chapter 3 led into a time skip to the end of the day, thus making it a great place to end a chapter.
I think it’s down to personal preference. It’s good to keep most of your chapters a uniform length. While not strictly required, knowing how much of a chapter is left and the average length of a chapter helps a reader determine whether they have the time to read a chapter before being busy.
Despite this upside, I wouldn’t recommend trying this because you may end up sacrificing things to achieve this. I won’t explain these sacrifices because this post is already long and deductive reasoning exists.

I think one of the prime reasons scifi has better appeal in certain circles is that tabletop gaming - mostly D&D - has become the 2200lb gorilla that many learn the tropes from.
And Star Wars falls solidly in the fantasy camp.
It's not that there's less scifi, so you're more free to write as you wish.
One you move away from the franchises there's more room to flex your worldbuiling with less research/effort.
I've read some awesome published fantasy that came damned close to historical fiction in level of detail, and I'm talking far more than ASoIaF or Wheel of Time.
Subverting the shadow of D&D's kitchen sink, much less Tolkien, can grow to an epic task.
